description: From Middle English cominge, comynge, comande, from Old English cumende, from Proto-Germanic *kwemandz, present participle of Proto-Germanic *kwemaną (“to come”), equivalent to come +‎ -ing (present participle ending). Cognate with Dutch komend (“coming”), German kommend (“coming”), Swedish kommande (“coming”), Icelandic komandi (“coming”).
From Middle English coming, commyng, cumming, equivalent to come +‎ -ing (gerundive ending).

entries.meaning: Approaching; of the future, especially the near future; the next.
examples: See you the/this Sunday coming! -Well, maybe I can't the/this coming Sunday but on Sunday week.
She will have two or three paintings in the coming exhibition.

entries.meaning: Newly in fashion; advancing into maturity or achievement.
examples: Ergonomic wallets are the coming thing.

entries.meaning: The act of arriving; an arrival.
